ğŸ‘‰
sed -i 's/Ahmad is here//g' ~/.ssh/keyp  
To substitute words and phrases
The -i means "do this in place," as in don't create another file. The capital I near the end stands for "case-insensitive" and means that whether â€˜ cows â€˜ has any capital letters in it or not, change it to Ants. The g means do it globally, throughout the whole file. Here is the complete command:
sed -i 's/cows/Ants/Ig' keyp
Now cat ~/.ssh/keyp

